Alliance of Exiled <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub3.ezboard.com/uarathena.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Arathena</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>   <font color=#CC9900>(7/6/00 1:24:15 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Paladins, Rangers and SK's, OH MY!!</span><hr size=1> You as a Ranger, Elbryon, are built on the same general thought line as myself as a Shadow Knight, or any pet Paladins I might have in my pocket. (The bards are a slightly different story, we'll come back to that.) This idea is power through despecialization. Myself, I'm really quite a mediocre tank. When you get right down to it, the Warrior beats me in AC, HP, and damage output, thanks to little things like Dual wielding and Critical attacks, and even kicks when they're using the same 2 hander I am. And we won't even go down the road of me trying to play as a necro. Yay, I can't even solo something 15 levels beneath me using pure caster strategies. Ergo, I suck, right? I can't damage like a warrior, and I can't uber solo like a necro. _Wrong!_ Because of the potent way I can _combine_ magic and melee, I make the truly top flight character class that you want to put into your group over that warrior, or that monk, or even that necro or mage. I'm the guy with some of the true uber taunts. Life tap. Siphon Strengh. Darkness line. Blood boil line. And only once have I HTed a monster that lived that didn't immediately want to hang my guts off the moon and stars. All this, and my pet and taps make me very close to self suffecient too. Enough so that all it takes in my party to take anything not specifically deigned to take 18+ people to take is a Paladin. <br>
<br>
However, I think I made that point before. More important is figuring out how _your_ magic can butress your melee, especially in a group. I know you're a valuable puller, almost as much so as myself, simply because you're the one with the skill to track down that ugly named mob, and you're the one with the bow to peg him from 200 range units off, and bring him steaming down on the rest of us. You've got DD, I know you have snare.. Do you have root? Even if you don't, it's not too hard to develop a sense of how much more whacking you're gonna have to do before the mob taunts on you. Pay attention to everything scrolling past in red and blue, and you'll figure it out fast enough. Why not step back just before, and try to snare/root? Once you succeed, pepper it with DD or arrows(Note I said pepper, not burn your whole mana bar), till you think that short dorfie pally, or that hall clogging ogrish SK has his attention good and solid? Or step back every so many thwacks, let the warrior taunt for a salvo or three, toss a <br>
heal on him, and dive back in?<br>
<br>
No, maybe this isn't as satisfying as being able to outdamage a warrior in melee, but it always seemed clear to me that the hybrid payed that price for much more flexibility. You are not a warrior, you are not a monk, you are not a druid. I am not a warrior, I am not a necro.  Don't expect what works for them to work the same for you. By combining lesser parts of each, you can come up with something that's more than the whole of either. That's the whole point. No, Verant hasn't manage to fine hair balance all the classes, but a rough balance does exist, and there's a hair thin like you have to walk to make sure that you use your potential to the fullest. Break out of the mold everyone else is in. Think when you play. Be a ranger, and not a warrior, and not a Dr00id. Somewhere, there's a combination of the two that will let you bring every last bit of advantage that 40% exp penalty brings you. And, if nothing else, think of the sheer havok a highly skilled group of 1 of each of the hybrids could wreak.<br>
<br>
Everything I've said here is, of course, tempered by the fact that I've not played a ranger at all, nor do I intend to until I've got a full set of Sky-planar Shadow Knight Armor. However, the basic point remains the same. Rangers are not supposed to bring the heavy melee damage of a warrior or monk to the group, nor are they supposed to bring the heavy, two handed blades of the Paladin or SK. You bring something much, much different, and it's up to you rangers to figure out just what it is. Personally, fron what I've seen, you're a blend of Rogue and Druid, more than anything else. You might not have sneak and evade, but there's _something_ in that druid part that makes up for it and more. Might not be what you think it is, but it's there, or they wouldn't have bothered making the class. <br>
